comment:
It's good you had this conversation. It's one people still need to have, partly because, as you pointed out, it's situations like this which damage attempts to seek awareness of and redress for serious cases of domestic abuse of women.
Depp may well have been abusive, but so far the only verifiable evidence of physical violence is of his wife hitting him, BY HER OWN ADMISSION.
I have been a victim of domestic abuse - on the one occasion I retaliated (by pushing him repeatedly away from me) my partner reported me to the police (the fact he immediately after I pushed him smashed a ceramic lamp next to my head into the wall didn't exactly make him look good to the cops, mind you). In that instance this was not a cut-and-dried case of assailant vs. victim. So many of them aren't. Prior and subsequent (including witnessed) instances of his abuse were much more obviously just him being abusive, but I also am aware you can't always simplify the issue to fit a narrative.
Good video. I didn't agree with all of it, but I don't have to. The conversation itself was important.
